    "long_instructions": "## Do This:\r\n\r\n1. Run the code and observe what happens. \r\n2. Run the test to see if that gives you any insights into the bug.\r\n3. Decide which debugging strategy would be useful for this buggy program. \r\n4. Iteratively refine and test the updates you make to the code.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n**Unit Guide**\r\n\r\nDocument your experience with this debugging challenge:\r\n- What strategy did you use? \r\n- How did it help?\r\n- When might it be most useful in the future?",
    "start_sources": {
      "files": {
        "0": {
          "id": "0",
          "name": "main.py",
          "language": "py",
          "contents": "from neighborhood import Painter\n\npainter = Painter()\n\ndef paint_path():\n    painter.paint(\"blue\")\n    painter.move()\n    painter.paint(\"yellow\")\n    \npaint_path()\npaint_path()\n",
          "folderId": "0",
          "active": true,
          "open": true
        }
      },
      "folders": {
      }
    },
    "teacher_markdown": "**Error Type**: Logic Error (Code does something unexpected)\r\n\r\n**Expected Outcome**: The `Painter` should move forward, turn left, and paint a blue and yellow tile.\r\n\r\nDebugging Challenge\r\n\r\n- The code runs, but it doesn’t behave as expected—it paints tiles on top of each other instead of in a straight path.\r\n- Students must determine why calling `paint_path()` twice causes overlapping tiles.\r\n- Hint for students: Use `print` statements to track the `Painter`’s position before and after each function call.",
    "display_name": "Debugging Challenge 2",
    "thumbnail_url": "https://images.code.org/588e0949748ba9e9208ece1b336cad20-debug.png",
    "bubble_choice_description": "Your `Painter` is hard at work, but something seems... off. You expected a nice pattern, but instead, the results are overlapping and messy. Can you figure out what’s going wrong and set things right?"
